    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for the intro. Some of my more skeptical students might ask why judges should have the power to decide which \"fundamental rights\" are protected instead of just letting the elected legislature decide. How should I explain the legitimacy of this power to them, especially since critics say it's basically just judges making up laws they like?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The legitimacy of judicial review in defining fundamental rights stems from the Constitution itself, which serves as the ultimate law, not the legislature. When the legislature infringes upon rights deemed essential to human dignity, the courts act as a necessary check against tyranny of the majority. This power is not about judges \"making up laws,\" but rather interpreting the enduring principles of liberty enshrined in the foundational document.",
      "source": "target",
