    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Interesting point. So, to make sure I've got this right for the lesson: if a legislature passes a law that is technically following all the correct procedures, but it's just something the judges don't personally agree with or see as \"fundamental,\" the judges can just strike it down? It sounds like it could be a very powerful way to bypass the will of the voters. How would you address that specific tension in class?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This tension is the very core of the American system of checks and balances, and it's a necessary friction. While it appears judges are bypassing voters, the Constitution itself is the ultimate sovereign, not the temporary will of a majority. When a law violates a fundamental, inherent right—like the right to privacy—the judiciary is upholding the higher law against transient political passions. This tension is what prevents the government from becoming an absolute dictatorship.",
      "source": "target",
